@* THE (ELEMENT, EVENT) KEY (decision 165). ONE element carrying TWO handlers -- @onsubmit and
   @onkeydown -- which is the shape that decides how the preventDefault rule may be keyed.

   The rule started life as a set of ELEMENT names. Repairing A1 by adding this form's element to that
   set would have suppressed its KEYDOWN as well (Blazor's table is submit-only) and, worse, would have
   handed the keydown arrow to a method that DECLARED a KeyboardEventArgs while passing it nothing:
   `e.Key` reading undefined, rendering fine, comparing against nothing. Blazor keys on the EVENT TYPE
   and so does this compiler now, so the two listeners on _el0 come out different on purpose:

       listen(_el0, 'submit',  (e) => { e.preventDefault(); … });
       listen(_el0, 'keydown', (e) => { lastKey.value = e.key; });   // untouched *@

<form @onsubmit="Save" @onkeydown="OnKey"><input id="name" @bind="name" /><button id="save" type="submit">save</button></form>
<p id="out">@saved</p>
<p id="key">@lastKey</p>

@code {
    private string name = "";
    private string saved = "";
    private string lastKey = "";

    void Save() { saved = name; }

    void OnKey(KeyboardEventArgs e) { lastKey = e.Key; }
}
